3) Results Summary

3.1 From Earth: top “night presences” (mean brightness when visible)

1) Jupiter (dominant giant, “kingmaker in the night”)
2) Saturn (second giant, “boundary-judge”)
3) Venus (bright, but tied to dawn/dusk—still high impact)
4) Mars
5) Mercury (visible often, but rarely far from Sun)

Interpretation: Earth’s sky naturally makes Jupiter/Saturn the heavyweight “authority pair,” while Venus is the alluring herald at the edges of day.

⸻

3.2 From Mars: what changes?

1) Jupiter
2) Saturn
3) Earth  ← big change
4) Venus
5) Uranus/Neptune (dim but “always there” if you have optics)

The killer insight:
From Mars, Earth behaves like Venus does from Earth: an interior planet, mostly near the Sun, appearing as a brilliant dawn/dusk object.

Even more crisp:
	•	Max elongation of Earth as seen from Mars (geometry):
\theta_{\max} \approx \arcsin\left(\frac{a_{\text{Earth}}}{a_{\text{Mars}}}\right)
= \arcsin\left(\frac{1}{1.524}\right)\approx 41^\circ
So Earth would be a true “Morning/Evening Star” from Mars, with a max separation similar in spirit to Venus’s from Earth.

Myth seed from Mars:
Earth becomes “The Blue Lantern”—a near-sun jewel, life-colored, capricious, associated with home, origin, water, memory, and promise.

